utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, no, no. But you said why is this woman allowed in the country because this was part of the argument which is blame Obama, blame Lynch. utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So if you guys say that the Russians interfered in the election and tilted it to Donald Trump, you were the ones that led the Trojan horse into the country to allow this big collusion to have your candidate lose? Is that your game?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I will take that game because you've got a losing hand. The fact is the woman with a lawyer --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Wait, wait, wait, we won.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You let the woman in.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I didn't. I'm telling you --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Obama let the woman in to sting (ph) Hillary. And now it's our fault?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You let the woman into the country that made Hillary lose.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Everybody talk at separate times, please.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK.

utterances.speaker: WATTTERS
utterances.utterance: Go ahead, Lisa.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes, Lisa, go.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: We've often see --

utterances.speaker: GUTLED
utterances.utterance: Because one doesn't have it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAM
utterances.utterance: I have it. You wouldn't let me answer.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: We've also seen so much self-righteous indignation from people that have no business being self-righteous. Like I absolutely love the fact that Robby Mook is out there and talking about --

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Who's Robby Mook?

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: The campaign manager for Hillary Clinton. He literally worked for the most soulless woman on this planet who would literally sell her daughter to be president if she should.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: Sell her only her child to be president. I mean that's how much she wanted. So I just think that there's like a little bit of irony here that these people are supposed to be the voices of authority on morality or ethical, you know, what's ethical or not given some of the people that they worked for.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, I don't know if anybody thinks Hillary's morality. Gutfeld, any last words on the story?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, I think -- and I think Juan would agree with me on this because Juan, you've been in journalism for a long time. What kills me is how the left -- OK, so when the USSR was a world power, you had a lot of apologists among liberal saying that we were overplaying the Cold War, we were overplaying the communist threat. If we had listened to them, the USSR never would have broken up. If we had to Ted Kennedy, the USSR would still be here and we'd be dealing with a geopolitical threat that would (INAUDIBLE) others. Now, we are dealing with a marginalized world power which is Russia. Russia is like on one-eight the power that it used to be. I'm being conservative on this. And now there are threats.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: So you see the hypocrisy here --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Where were you guys in the `80s?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Where were you guys in the `80s? And now you're scared of them --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yeah, yeah. OK, OK. Let me just say ---

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Did you see my point?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Do you remember where the Democrats were fighting against the Russians in the Cuban missile prices and Sputnik?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Those were the conservatives now, Juan.

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: But it doesn't matter because in modern times if you think it's a 1980s foreign policy and they called it and they need it back and no Democrats cross this seriously. At any point for the last --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: In the `80s?

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: No, it's the same remark Obama said to Mitt Romney during the debate.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, that. OK.

utterances.speaker: GODLY
utterances.utterance: Come on, you know what that is.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, I do. But I want it to come back --

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: But I'm just saying Obama -- the reason why Putin and Russia has any strength and whatsoever is because Democrats completely ignored his expansion into the Baltic space.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yup.

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: They have everything globally for the past eight years. The fact they are crying wolf now is because it's politically expedient. Give me a break.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK. So -- but I think that at the moment you guys are running away from the news of the day, and I'm just --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: We're doing it in the lead of the show.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, no. What you're doing is saying it didn't matter.

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: I'm not running away from anything.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But I am struck by the fact that Charles Grassley, a Republican, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, said the man that was identified is in the meeting today was a self-acknowledged Russian spy.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He's also an American citizen.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: He's also spy, Greg.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Russian spy according to you?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No. You just assumed everybody is a spy.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Is that right?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: When you had the box on your head I would --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Don't body slam him, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Far left MSNBC host Joy Reid does it again making some wild general accusations about the Republican Party. What she is saying now, next.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: It seems like nothing is off the table for MSNBC host Joy Reid when it comes to slamming the Republican Party. She caused an uproar when she went after Congressman Steve Scalise while he was hospitalized after the assassination attack.

utterances.speaker: JOY REID, MSNBC HOST
utterances.utterance: It's a delicate thing because, you know, obviously, everybody is wishing the Congressman well and hoping that he recovers. But Steve Scalise has a history that we've all been force to sort of ignore on race --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Now, she's added it again latching out the entire GOP this time.

utterances.speaker: REID
utterances.utterance: Donald Trump didn't invest this. He didn't invent this Republican Party. He just saw the trends and took advantage of it. This the Republican Party that's been built on resentment and a sense of victimhood, a sense of persecution, almost a persecution complex for more than 40 years, almost 50 years going back to the dawn of the civil rights movement when they felt persecuted by the world.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So, Meghan, you know the GOP, and I'm going to ask, do you think that this is a rational argument to say that GOP says oh, you know, we don't like Hollywood. We can't stand the college elites and the professors. People in the mainstream media are bias against us. Is that a legitimate argument as we hear --

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: No, that woman knows nothing about GOP politics. I would like to know the last time she left New York City and actually talked to a Republican voter in their home state, number one.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Ouch.

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: Number two, the entire fuel that fuels the Democratic Party is victimhood right now. Number one, so it's hilarious that she even point that at Republicans. Across the country right now at Democratic dinner is they are removing President Andrew Jackson from all meetings, Andrew Jackson and Jefferson because they think that they are racist and they don't want them in their dinners anymore. Today, a bunch of congressman --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Wait. Slow down. I didn't understand. What do you mean?

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: They're removing them from the platform because they don't want Andrew Jackson and Jefferson around because they think they are racist --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, the annual dinners you mean.

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes, got it.

utterances.speaker: GODLEY
utterances.utterance: And going forward today, a bunch of Democratic congresswomen paraded around sleeveless because they wanted to show that the sexist regime, which by the way happened under Nancy Pelosi of the dress code in -- excuse me, and Congress ended being removed today. So, I just think the entire Democratic platform is about victimhood and the idea she knows anything about Republican politics is hilarious.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: What would you say, Lisa?

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: Well, I just think how gross and distasteful her comments about Steve Scalise. And then also to Meghan's point, it's the Democratic Party that plays this victim card constantly. I mean, what did Jennifer Palmieri are due after the election she stood at the Harvard University event with Kellyanne Conway and she proceeded to blamed sexism, racism on the reason that President Donald Trump won.

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: I mean, this is the card the Democratic play, card that they continuously play like a talk, is the victim card. I mean, that's constantly the only card they are playing.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, just for a second. Let's imagine that she had some basis for saying --

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: But she doesn't.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: The Republican Party celebrates their grievance. Is that fair?

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: No, in what context? How do they do that? That's the --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I said to you, Hollywood -- wait. Hollywood is against us say the Republicans, academics and colleges are against us, Black Lives Matter against us.

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: The west is in love with the idea of being victims. Their entire platform is on the onus, they are a victim in one context or another. So, the idea that Republicans are doing that is not only ironic but wildly inaccurate on the platform of the Republican Party. She may not like why President Trump won because he actually talked to voters in the middle of the country and listen to their problems and talked about issues like coal and jobs and ISIS instead of things trans rights that's obviously don't have the same breath of effect on voters. They're talking about real issues. But it is none of her concern. What she needs to be concerned about is talking to the voters that they lost. And when you're in this bubble at MSNBC judging conservatives in the middle of the country, you're sure as hell not going to win them back over.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So, Jesse, part of her argument again trying to really understanding what she's saying is Donald Trump right now is being enabled by people like Paul Ryan, Speaker of the House, and others in the Congress. They won't say a word against him and that Donald Trump is so powerful. He has made the GOP accept anything, that nothing he does is objectionable to any Republican at the moment.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I mean, I think the Republican Party feel unfairly persecuted by Hollywood--

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- by the media, by the Democratic Party, by the IRS.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes. Keep going.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And -- I mean, I could keep you all day.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So -- and I think that's a justifiable motion. At the same time, I happen to agree with my colleagues here that the Democratic Party is actually the party of victimhood. The Democratic Party has been fertilized by victimization for many, many years. If you think about the identity of politics, as Greg likes to talk about, it's all about victimhood, yet blacks are the victims of white oppression. Gays are the victims of Christians. Women are the victims of men. Muslims are the victims of our government. Big government liberalism is predicated on defending the victims of capitalism. Big banks, big oil, big pharma prey on victims. And since socially, liberals set-up a dynamic where they have to swoop in and save these victims from these people. So the poor, the victims of the rich, criminals are the victims of police, and then illegal immigrants are the victims of ISIS.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I get it, I get it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So it's all about predator versus prey and then you need big government to come in and then save these people--

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: It's a political.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- and make them dependent.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So they need them for votes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: All right. I have--

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: It's a political. Exactly.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: As the last person I state that go to the panel this Friday night is Mr. I hate this people, Greg Gutfeld.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I love these people.

utterances.speaker: WILLILAMS
utterances.utterance: You got -- I got them.

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: Why?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I'm always troubled but --

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: Why?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It's interesting that everybody named Joy is always bitter and angry. I only two people named Joy. Joy Behar and Joy -- what's her last name?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Reid.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Joy Reid. They're just angry people. Look, conservative or Republicans, they didn't create safe spaces on campuses. They didn't create -- they didn't define the term micro aggression. They didn't create speak -- speech codes. These are all coming from the progressive or what you could call now as the regressive left. Right now in -- identity politics is falling apart because it's finally being exposed with -- when you look at Evergreen College, that scandal. So I think what's happening is she's projecting her own scene as a defense because she might feel that her belief system is crumbling. Right now in Canada, they passed the law that can -- you can go to prison if you use the wrong pronoun. This is the first time. You can go to jail if you don't use the word -- if you don't use the right word. They're mandating language. This is scary stuff. This isn't -- is born from the oppressor versus the oppressed ideology. The victim with ideology is that your words can actually hurt. So this is actually dangerous thing and I think that because people are waking up to it, she feels threatened. And that's why she's projecting.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But Greg, just her --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- tells me for a second. Don't you think it's true, when you scream I hate these people--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: --that lots of people, Republicans, conservatives say, thank God, because I hate these people too. And this is a Republican perspective. You hear it on talk radio all the time. utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: One, if you look at the -- I've never done -- hate these people of Black Lives Matter. I've never done that. I do it about people texting when they're crossing the street. I hate these people is based on specific behaviors that I find annoying.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: What about --

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: -- which are universally annoying despite what color of your skin is, what sex you are --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: My hate transcends. It transcends any kind of identity or pigment or ethnicity --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I hate everybody equally.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Equal opportunity hater.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: But it's the Democratic Party that is constantly seeing people through the lens, as you had mentioned, through a black, white, us, whatever your sex is. And Hillary Clinton was the one that ran a campaign and there's a special place in hell for women that don't vote for her.

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: So please spare me, Joy Reid, go be joyful, maybe change your attitude.

utterances.utterance: All right. Ahead, is the top Democratic in the House changing her position on the impeachment call coming from her own party? We're going to hear from Nancy Pelosi, next.

utterances.utterance: Democrats love to talk about ousting President Trump from office this week, one congressman took action. Brad Sherman from California filed the first articles of impeachment. House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi typically cautioned her party against impeachment talk. But now she seems open to the idea.

utterances.speaker: REP. NANCY PELOSI, D-CALI., HOUSE MINORITY LEADER
utterances.utterance: There's evidence, clear evidence that we -- we need to know more and we should not close that path. I have always been reluctant, because I think impeachment is something that really has an impact on the country. So when the facts are clear, the law is certainly clear, when the facts are clear, then this Congress will make a decision in that regard.

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: Another prominent Democrat like Jesse Jackson are still trying to invalidate the election.

utterances.speaker: JESSE JACKSON, CIVIL RIGHTS ACTIVIST
utterances.utterance: Don't let them fool you. We worked last year. We won the election. It was stolen.

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: OK. The people are upset. Let us show the deal. Lisa, 2018 midterms are going to be the impeachment election. Democrats were talking about impeachment on election night when Trump got elected. I'm not looking forward to what I think is a losing message for Democrats. I think if you can see anything from the special elections, like Jon Ossoff, it doesn't work. It doesn't seem you resonate with voters. Why hitch yourself to a message that clearly isn't resonating?

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: They also have been fund-raising. In the Georgia Six special election, Jon Ossoff didn't mention President Trump once when he is advertising. There is a reason for that. He wasn't as politically poisoned as Democrats thought they were in that congressional district. Look, they have been trying to undermine the president as you mentioned from day one. They blamed everything under the sun for the reason why Hillary Clinton lost. Racism and sexism as we head during the previous segment. They also tried to hijack this Russian investigation as well to try to undermine the president and hurt him politically. They can't come to terms with the fact that President Trump -- nearly 700 counties that twice went to President Obama, one-third flipped for Trump. Also, you look -- he won 194 of the 207 counties that either went for Obama in 2008 or 2012. This is serious stuff. President Trump was able to resonate with voters in a way that Hillary Clinton wasn't able to do. And so I think that they are overreaching in (inaudible) to not wake up to that fact.

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: Juan, wonder if you're someone like a Democrat like yourself, Nancy Pelosi still has her iron grip like an iron throne on power and she is not letting people like Tim Ryan who could actually resonate with the middle of the country and start winning over some of the Trump voters because it's all about her. Doesn't that matter that is about the party. Doesn't that frustrate you?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No. Tim Ryan is a congressman from Ohio who challenged Pelosi for her minority leadership of the house. And he lost. I think he lost -- I think you might appreciate this, because Pelosi has a record as a great fundraiser. And guess what? Going back to the passage and I know some popular among Republicans, but passage of things like the Affordable Care Act, Pelosi was a leader among Democrats. And she remains, as you said, you can say iron grip. I appreciate that.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: (inaudible) to be proud of.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But I want to say --

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: It doesn't matter how money you dump into election, like it shows with Ossoff.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Money doesn't matter?

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: I don't think it matters when you don't have the right message. It was the most expensive congressional election in history.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think that was a heavily Republican district. But my point this Friday night. Because everybody has been talking drinking.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Who?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Not fake news.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Here is a recent poll, 73 percent of Democrats would give up alcohol for the rest of their lives if Donald Trump were impeached tomorrow.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: That's crazy.

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: I know. I drank with plenty of them. They can't hold their alcohol.

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: What do you think about the impeachment talk?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That actually does say a lot about how zest --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- and compulsive they are about this idea. They are still living in the past. They are (inaudible) the past because they feel right now that they don't have a future. But it's not a vision. It's a tantrum. I don't want to help them, but I will help them. Instead of spurning, they should be learning from Donald Trump. What were the three things that he nailed the Democrats for? There was the perception of being anti-law and order and anti-security. The liberals are soft on that stuff. Embracing identity politics. He said no. Let's be Americans. Let's forget about divisiveness. The third thing is, he really did embrace freedom of speech by basically saying whatever he wanted. Meanwhile, the albatross around the liberals' neck is the speech coach in which going on campus. So a thoughtful Democrat with a vision who could win has to embrace law and order, has to reject speech coach and also has to reject identity politics, and they could win. If they don't do that, they're screwed.

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: Not Elizabeth Warren.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Not.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Every Democrat watching did not pay any attention in what Greg Gutfeld say because that was right on. I don't think the Democrats can accept the rule of the people so they are trying to overturn the rule of the people.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Just listen to what they did since the election. The election was hacked. The election was stolen. They played games with the popular vote, you know. He didn't get the popular vote. John Lewis said, Trump was not a legitimate president. The congressional black caucus. He is not my president was a hash tag. They boycotted the inauguration.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: That's true.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: They are putting impeachment. Now, they are putting this idea that they can use the 25th amendment to remove him from office because he is mentally unfit. They have accused him of treason. And now they are showering with leaks so they undermine him. Now, I think if the Democrats got the house or the senate, they could have fought President Trump within the system. But now they have nothing. So they have to rely on these things. If they get rid of Trump, you know who they have?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Pence.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Will they like Pence? I don't think so.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But you don't think Trump has said anything to hurt himself?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'm not going to argue with that. But he's done a lot to help himself.

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: All right. We have to move on unfortunately, but I could talk about this all night, but i do love this next story ahead. Musician Kid Rock is running for senate and Senator Elizabeth Warren is flipping out. We'll tell you about it next.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: You guys missed Meghan singing.

utterances.utterance: Is Kid Rock kidding or is he really considering launching a senate bid? The singer promised to make announcement soon on Twitter after unveiling the website kidrockforsenate.com. The Michigan native said it's not a hoax, but some are questioning as it coincides with the release of two new music videos. Democratic Senator Elizabeth Warren (inaudible) the possibility. Warren supporters view it, you know, maybe this is all a joke, but we all thought Donald Trump was a joke when he rode down the escalator at Trump Tower and announced his campaign, too. So, Greg, is this a joke or do you think we are going to see Kid Rock for senate?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I have no idea, but Elizabeth Warren is right. She actually -- I never said that before in my life. I would call this the Trump effect.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: When people think if he can do it, so can I. It's a healthy sentiment. We need more every man types. You know, what's really good? It's good for people who have a past. A lot of people don't run because they go oh, man!

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I have known him for a while. Back in my days of the magazine. I think about -- was that a name drop?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: A little bit.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I knew Bob gone way back. His real name is Bob. Anyway, I hope he does. He is an everyman interesting guy. He's a smart dude.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: Yes. Meghan, what do you think? He hasn't filled out any paperwork yet, but he saying that he has got 15 days to file. What do you think?

utterances.speaker: MCCAIN
utterances.utterance: I don't know. I think tax cuts, guns and strippers sound like a pretty all-American platform to me.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.utterance: Are you envisioning the bumper sticker?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Juan can get excited about that.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I was dumbstruck.
